        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              The United States conducted nearly 200 atmospheric nuclear weapons
              development tests from 1945 to 1962. Credits: Atomic Archive</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            After 80 years, generations of New Mexicans are finally included in
            a
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-17-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-federal-compensation-program?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >federal compensation program</a
            >
            for radiation-linked health problems tied to the 1945 Trinity test.
            The 2025 Republican tax bill recently expanded its compensation
            program, providing up to $25,000 in benefits, including support for
            the families of deceased individuals.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            A
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-17-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-2023-study?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >2023 study</a
            >
            found that 101 nuclear weapons were tested, and the fallout spread
            across 46 US states, Mexico, and Canada, contaminating air, water,
            and food. Over 10,000 New Mexicans still suffer radiation-linked
            illnesses.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            Advocates warn that the two-year application deadline for the
            compensation program, which ends in 2027, will make application
            assimilation difficult. The program also states that compensation is
            provided if the person resided in one of the affected areas between
            1945 and 1962, which eliminates many victim.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
